{{Infobox power station | name = Holaniku at Keahole Point | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Hawaii | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= Location of Holaniku at Keahole Point solar farm in Hawaii | coordinates = {{coord|19|42|54|N|156|2|7|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = United States | location = [[Kona District, Hawaii]] | status = O | construction_began = {{start date|2006|01|01}} | commissioned = {{start date|2009|03|16}} | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = Keahole Solar Power | operator = | solar_type = CSP | solar_csp_technology= P | ps_units_operational= 1,000 | solar_csp_collectors= | ps_units_manu_model = | solar_site_area = {{convert|3|acre|m2|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=nrel/> | ps_electrical_capacity= 2&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac= 2%<ref name=nrel>{{cite web|title= Holaniku at Keahole Point|url= http://www.nrel.gov/csp/solarpaces/project_detail.cfm/projectID=71|publisher = [[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]]|accessdate= 2011-12-03}}</ref> | website = | extra = }} '''Holaniku at Keahole Point''' is a 2[[megawatt|MW]] micro-scaled [[concentrated solar power]] plant in the [[Kona District, Hawaii|Kona District]] (west coast) of the [[Hawaii (island)|island of Hawai{{Okina}}i]]. It is located in the [[Natural Energy Laboratory of Hawaii]] at [[Keahole Point]].<ref name=reporter> {{cite news |last=Prevedouros|first=Panos |title=DHHL and PUC Should be Cautious with Proposed Solar Power Plant on Oahu |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/dhhl-and-puc-should-be-cautious-with-proposed-solar-power-plant-on-oahu/123 |newspaper = Hawaii Reporter |date = 2011-07-26 |accessdate = 2011-12-22}} </ref>
Holaniku at Keahole Point is the first commercial [[List of solar thermal power stations|solar thermal power plant]] to be built using solar collectors manufactured by [[Sopogy]]. The project was developed by Keahole Solar Power, LLC. an Engineering, Procurement, and Contracting ([[EPC (contract)|EPC]]) company. The plant contains over 1,000 Sopogy MicroCSP SopoNova [[parabolic trough]] solar collectors. The power plant uses the sun's heat to create steam.<ref name="power-technology.com"> {{cite web |title= Holaniku at Keahole Point Micro CSP Thermal Plant, Kona Desert, Hawaii, USA |url= http://www.power-technology.com/projects/holanikuatkeaholepoi/ |publisher = Net Resources International |work = power-technology.com |accessdate= 2010-08-07}}{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}} </ref> Most of the steam created is used onsite for other experimental uses, equating to only 0.5MW maximum that can be utilized to generate electricity. Little, if any, electrical power leaves the site and enters the state electrical grid.
