{{primary sources|date=September 2017}}
{{onesource|date=May 2016}}
'''MKM steel''', an [[alloy]] containing [[nickel]] and [[aluminum]], was developed in 1931 by the [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[metallurgist]] [[Tokuhichi Mishima]]. While conducting research into the properties of nickel, Mishima discovered that a strongly [[magnetic]] [[steel]] could be created by adding aluminum to non-magnetic nickel steel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tokushichi Mishima MK Magnetic Steel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303190607/http://www.jpo.go.jp/seido_e/rekishi_e/tokushi_mishima.htm|url=https://www.jpo.go.jp/seido_e/rekishi_e/tokushi_mishima.htm|website=japan Patent Office|archive-date=3 March 2016|date=7 October 2002}}</ref> 

==Characteristics==
The developers claim MKM steel is tough and durable, inexpensive to produce, maintains strong [[magnetism]] when [[miniaturized]] and can produce a stable [[magnetic force]] in spite of temperature changes or vibration.  MKM steel is similar to [[Alnico]].{{cn|date=May 2016}}

==Acronym==
MKM is an [[acronym]] for Mitsujima ka magnetic, 'Mitsujima ka' being the name of the inventor's childhood home.{{cn|date=May 2016}}

